          "body": "The chapter's last movement (3:18-20) inverts the Corinthians' self-assessment. They thought their party-loyalties marked them as *sophoi* — wise insiders to deeper truth. Paul's answer is to quote Job 5:13 and Psalm 94:11: the wisdom of this world is *moria* (foolishness) before God, and the reasonings of the wise are *mataioi* (useless). The path to genuine wisdom requires self-emptying — *let him become a fool, that he may become wise* (3:18). This is the cruciform epistemology of 1:18-25 applied directly: only the one who has accepted the apparent foolishness of the cross has access to the wisdom that actually saves."
